<theorem xml:id="thm-adsf">
  <statement>
    <p>If <m>f'(x)=0</m> on an interval <m>[a,b]</m>, then <m>f(x)=C</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>.      
    </p>
  </statement>
</theorem>
<proof>
  <p>
    Set <m>C=f(a)</m>. For any <m>x\in (a,b]</m> we know that <me>f(x)-f(a)=f'(\xi)(x-a)</me> for some <m>\xi\in(a,b)</m> by the Mean Value Theorem. Since <m>f'(\xi)=0</m>, <m>f(x)=f(a)=C</m> as desired.
  </p>
</proof>

